                <h2 class=3D"text question" style=3D"font-size:medium; font=
-style:italic; margin-top:30px">How do I use the Quadratic Formula?</h2>
                <p class=3D"text">To use the Quadratic Formula, you must:</=
p>
                <ul>
                  <li><p class=3D"text">Arrange your equation into the form=
 "(quadratic) <span class=3D"math">=3D 0</span>".</p></li>
                  <li><p class=3D"text">Arrange the terms in the (equation)=
 in decreasing order (so squared term first, then the <span class=3D"math">=
<em>x</em></span>-term, and finally the linear term).</p></li>
                  <li><p class=3D"text">Pull out the numerical parts of eac=
h of these terms, which are the "<span class=3D"math"><em>a</em></span>", "=
<span class=3D"math"><em>b</em></span>", and "<span class=3D"math"><em>c</e=
m></span>" of the Formula.</p></li>
                  <li><p class=3D"text">Plug these numbers into the formula=
.</p></li>
                  <li><p class=3D"text">Simplify to get your answers.</p></=
li>
                </ul>
                <p class=3D"text">Advisories: The "<span class=3D"math">2<e=
m>a</em></span>" in the denominator of the Formula is underneath everything=
 above, not just the square root. And it's a "<span class=3D"math">2<em>a</=
em></span>" under there, not just a plain "<span class=3D"math">2</span>". =
Make sure that you are careful not to drop the square root or the "plus/min=
us" in the middle of your calculations, or I can guarantee that you will fo=
rget to "put them back in" on your test, and you'll mess yourself up. Remem=
ber that "<span class=3D"math"><em>b</em><sup>2</sup></span>" means "the sq=
uare of ALL of <span class=3D"math"><em>b</em></span>, including its sign",=
 so don't leave <span class=3D"math"><em>b</em><sup>2</sup></span> being ne=
gative, even if <span class=3D"math"><em>b</em></span> is negative, because=
 the square of a negative is a positive.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">In other words, don't be sloppy and don't=
 try to take shortcuts, because it will only hurt you in the long run. Trus=
t me on this!</p>
                <h2 class=3D"text question" style=3D"font-size:medium; font=
-style:italic;">What is an example of using the Quadratic Formula?</h2>
                <ul>
                  <li><h4 class=3D"text question">Solve <span class=3D"math=
"><em>x</em><sup>2</sup> + 3<em>x</em> =E2=88=92 4 =3D 0</span></h4></li>
                </ul>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">This quadratic happens to factor, which=
 I can use to confirm what I get from the Quadratic Formula. The Formula sh=
ould give me the same answers.</p>
                  <p class=3D"math" style=3D"text-indent:20px;"><em>x</em><=
sup>2</sup> + 3<em>x</em> =E2=88=92 4 =3D (<em>x</em> + 4)(<em>x</em> =E2=
=88=92 1) =3D 0</p>
                  <p class=3D"text">...so I already know that the solutions=
 are <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em> =3D =E2=88=924</span> and <span class=
=3D"math"><em>x</em> =3D 1</span>.</p>
                  <p class=3D"text">Now, what would my solution look like i=
n the Quadratic Formula? Using <span class=3D"math"><em>a</em> =3D 1</span>=
, <span class=3D"math"><em>b</em> =3D 3</span>, and <span class=3D"math"><e=
m>c</em> =3D =E2=88=924</span>, my solution process looks like this:</p>
                  <div id=3D"qform02A" style=3D"margin-left:20px;"><span cl=
ass=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org=
/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mstyle displayst=
yle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0"><mfrac><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mo stretchy=
=3D"false">(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo><mo>=C2=B1</mo><msq=
rt><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mo stretchy=3D"false=
">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mn>4</mn><mo stretchy=3D"false"=
>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>=
<mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mn>4</mn><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>=E2=80=89</mrow></=
msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo str=
etchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">x =3D \dfrac{-(3) \pm \sqrt{(3)^2 - 4(1)(-4)\,}}{2(1=
