                <h2 class=3D"text question" style=3D"font-size:medium; font=
-style:italic;">How does the Quadratic Formula relate to <span class=3D"mat=
h">x</span>-intercepts?</h2>
                <p class=3D"text">The solutions to the quadratic equation, =
as provided by the Quadratic Formula, are the <span class=3D"math"><em>x</e=
m></span>-intercepts of the corresponding graphed parabola.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">How? Well, when <span class=3D"math"><em>=
y</em> =3D 0</span>, you're on the <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-a=
xis. The <a href=3D"https://www.purplemath.com/modules/intrcept.htm"><span =
class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-intercepts</a> of the graph are where the =
parabola crosses the <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-axis. You're ap=
plying the Quadratic Formula to the equation <span class=3D"math"><em>ax</e=
m><sup>2</sup> + <em>bx</em> + <em>c</em> =3D <em>y</em></span>, where <spa=
n class=3D"math">y</span> is set equal to zero.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">Looking at the above example, there were =
two solutions for the equation <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em><sup>2</sup> =
+ 3<em>x</em> =E2=88=92 4 =3D 0</span>. This tells us that there must then =
be two <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-intercepts on the graph. Grap=
hing, we get the curve below:</p>
                <p style=3D"text-indent:20px;"><img src=3D"https://www.purp=
lemath.com/modules/quads/qform03.gif" alt=3D"y =3D x^2 + 3x - 4" width=3D"1=
95" height=3D"253"></p>
