                <p class=3D"text">As you can see, the <span class=3D"math">=
<em>x</em></span>-intercepts (the red dots above) match the solutions, cros=
sing the <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-axis at
<span class=3D"math"><em>x</em> =3D =E2=88=924</span> and <span class=3D"ma=
th"><em>x</em> =3D 1</span>. This shows the connection between graphing and=
 solving: When you are solving "(quadratic) <span class=3D"math">=3D 0</spa=
n>", you are finding the <span class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-intercepts =
of the graph. This can be useful if you have a graphing calculator, because=
 you can use the Quadratic Formula (when necessary) to solve a quadratic, a=
nd then use your graphing calculator to make sure that the displayed <span =
class=3D"math"><em>x</em></span>-intercepts have the same decimal values as=
 do the solutions provided by the Quadratic Formula.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">Note, however, that the calculator's disp=
lay of the graph will probably have some pixel-related round-off error, so =
you'd be checking to see that the computed and graphed values were reasonab=
ly close; don't expect an exact match.</p>
